COURSES.name: Financial Accounting and Reporting 1
COURSES.description: Covers the theoretical structure of financial accounting, required financial statements, revenue recognition, operating assets and current liabilities.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 2021 and ACG 2071 with minimum grades of B) and score of 70% on the Fisher School of Accounting Financial Accounting Competency Assessment and score of 70% on the Fisher School of Accounting Managerial Competency Assessment.

COURSES.name: Business Processes and Accounting Information System
COURSES.description: Examination of the accounting information systems in a business organization. Coverage extends over topics such as business processes, internal controls, and the fundamentals of accounting information systems analysis, design, implementation and control.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: (ACG 2021 and ACG 2071 with minimum grades of B) and (CGS 2531 or ISM
3013).

COURSES.name: Professional Speakers Series
COURSES.description: To expose students to technical topics and emerging issues in accounting, business and related professions such as law. The course addresses career opportunities in the practice of public accounting, industry, financial services, government, and in business more generally. (S-U)

COURSES.name: Financial Accounting and Reporting 2
COURSES.description: Continuation of ACG 3101 and includes coverage of accounting for investments, non-current liabilities and equities, accounting for income taxes, derivatives, accounting changes, statement of cash flows and earnings per share.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 3101 with minimum grade of C and FIN 3403.

COURSES.name: Cost and Managerial Accounting
COURSES.description: Extends cost and managerial coverage beyond that covered in ACG 2071. Topics include quantitative cost estimation, standard costing, flexible budgets, inventory management, pricing decisions, balanced scorecard, costs of quality, capital budgeting, transfer pricing and performance evaluations.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: (ACG 3101 and ACG 3401 with minimum grades of C) and QMB 3250 and (MAC
2234 or MAC 2312).

COURSES.name: Supervised Accounting Internship
COURSES.description: Applied work in professional accounting. Requires several papers and reports. (S-U)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: advanced permission of accounting internship coordinator.

COURSES.name: Honors Thesis
COURSES.description: The thesis must be submitted to the Fisher School no later than the published deadline and includes an abstract. (S-U)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Minimum 3.6 overall and a minimum 3.6 accounting GPA is required to earn the magna cum laude distinction. Minimum 3.8 overall and a minimum 3.8 accounting GPA is required to earn the summa cum laude distinction.

COURSES.name: Financial Accounting
COURSES.description: Introduction for prospective managers. Primary emphasis on financial reporting and analysis.

COURSES.name: Governmental Accounting
COURSES.description: Reporting by state and local governmental organizations and not-for-profit entities.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 7AC standing; ACG 5226

COURSES.name: Auditing I
COURSES.description: Concepts and theory underlying the audit of third party assertions. Coverage includes the audit environment, risk assessment, evidential search and evaluation, internal controls, audit programs and audit reporting.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 4111 and ACG 4341 with minimum grades of C, senior standing or higher, accounting major) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, and ACG 5075 with minimum grade of C).

COURSES.name: Auditing II
COURSES.description: Second of a two course sequence. Applies the concepts and theory of auditing to gain assurance about key business processes and financial statement assertions. Coverage includes: audit sampling, revenue process, acquisition process, human resource management process, inventory management, resource management processes; completion activities, audit reports and subsequent events.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 5637 or ACG 4632 with minimum grades of C, senior standing or higher, accounting major) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, ACG 5637 with minimum grade of C).

COURSES.name: Financial Reporting and Analysis
COURSES.description: Analyzing a firm's financial and accounting information from a user's perspective on financial reporting. Topics include: integration of firm strategy with accounting information content, effects of alternative accounting principles, and how accounting measures can be used as anchors for valuation.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5226, Class GE 7, and College EQ AC.

COURSES.name: Issues in Audit Practice
COURSES.description: In-depth discussion of fundamental concepts underlying audit practice, including introduction to current topics in auditing, advanced audit methods, and trends in auditing practice.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (Master of Accounting student, ACG 5815 and ACG 5226 with minimum grades of C) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, ACG 5647 with minimum grade of C).

COURSES.name: Information Systems Assurance
COURSES.description: Concepts of risk, control, and assurance in environments with advanced information technology. Technology based audit tools and techniques.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (Master of Accounting student, ACG 5647 and ACG 5226 with minimum grades of C) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, ACG 5647 with minimum grade of C).

COURSES.name: Individual Work in Accounting
COURSES.description: Reading and research in areas of accounting.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: approval of graduate coordinator.

COURSES.name: Advertising Strategy
COURSES.description: Overview of the strategic planning process required to develop a successful strategic, persuasive communication plan such as an advertising, integrated marketing communications, or social marketing campaign. Case studies and projects teach the skills needed to address a variety of communications management issues and engage audiences in diverse marketplaces.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C and ADV major.

COURSES.name: Principles of Advertising
COURSES.description: Overview of the concepts, strategies, and tactics of modern advertising. Explores the role of advertising in society, culture, and economics, as well as the industry and its key organizations. Introduces specific practices used to develop, place, and evaluate both traditional and digital ads.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: sophomore standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Cross Media Selling
COURSES.description: Explore traditional and digital media landscapes as well as the fundamental ways to create client-centered, holistic solutions using cross media platform selling. This course will deep dive into real-life examples and scenarios as well as give students hands-on experience with this type of selling.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C.

COURSES.name: Branding
COURSES.description: Principles of branding and brand strategy; learn to think creatively and critically about strategies and tactics applied to build and manage brands with insight into diverse audiences.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C.

COURSES.name: Multicultural Advertising in the US
COURSES.description: Studies multicultural communities and the process of developing advertising, promotional, and media communication tactics. Explores the methods of utilizing insights, research, and audience segmentation for developing and evaluating campaign development, while understanding the social, psychological, and cultural framework of diverse audiences.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C.

COURSES.name: Digital Insights
COURSES.description: Acquiring, evaluating, and analyzing information for advertising decisions. Emphasizes understanding the scientific method, developing explicit and measurable research objectives, selecting appropriate methodologies, and analyzing data.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C and STA 2023 and ADV major.

COURSES.name: Advertising Sales
COURSES.description: Principles of selling media time and space to advertisers. An overview of sales opportunities and challenges in the various advertising media. How to prepare and deliver effective sales presentations.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C and junior standing or higher in ADV.

COURSES.name: Professional Workshop in Advertising: Preparing Your Pitch
COURSES.description: Short-term intensive workshops in selected areas of professional development, skills, and projects. Workshops taught by professionals and often occur over three-day weekend periods. Topics change from semester to semester, with a focus on industry skills and subjects learned best from within a professional context.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 with a minimum grade of C.

COURSES.name: The Agency Immersion
COURSES.description: The Agency is an innovative, real-world advertising and public relations firm at UF that offers students an opportunity to build their expertise and gain experience in a hands-on environment, working directly with clients and industry professionals. Real-world work in a diverse and inclusive team environment will help you gain relevant experience, hone your skills through client feedback, gain industry access and perspective, and build a robust résumé and portfolio.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV major and sophomore standing.

COURSES.name: Copywriting and Visualization
COURSES.description: Application of creative strategy/concepts, copywriting and design to the creation of advertising for traditional and nontraditional media. To evaluate and present creative work, create ads for multicultural audiences.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Junior College of Journalism and Communications student; minimum grades of C or better in ENC 3252, ADV 3001 and VIC 3001. Coreq: ADV 3500.

COURSES.name: Media Planning
COURSES.description: Provides an in-depth overview of the media planning process. Emphasizes the value of various media channels and evaluation methods to design innovative and integrated media strategies to reach and engage diverse audiences.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 3JM ADV; minimum grades of C in ADV 3001 and ADV 3500.

COURSES.name: Great Ideas in Marketplace Communications
COURSES.description: Focuses on two aspects of strategic communications. First: creating, developing and producing advertising and promotional content for real live case studies. Second: evaluating topical issues and industry innovation in media content innovation.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and ENC 3252 and junior standing or higher in ADV.

COURSES.name: International and Cross Cultural Advertising
COURSES.description: Major concepts and issues in international and cross cultural advertising campaign planning including primary and secondary research to assess environmental situations, setting objectives, budgeting, media, creative, ethics and social responsibility.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 with a minimum grade of C.

COURSES.name: Advertising Portfolio I: Traditional Media Basics
COURSES.description: Create concepts through hands-on experiential learning while working on typical ad agency projects. Explores all the traditional media: TV, radio, print, OOH, guerrilla, and in-store pieces.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Advertising major and minimum grades of C in VIC 3001 and ADV 3001; Coreq: ADV 4101.

COURSES.name: Advertising Campaigns
COURSES.description: An advanced advertising course requiring the student to prepare and produce a complete general advertising campaign. Emphasis is placed on production methods, costs, research and media analysis.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 4JM ADV; minimum grades of C or better in ADV 4101 and ADV 4300.

COURSES.name: Individual Problems
COURSES.description: The student and instructor will choose a problem or project which provides experience in the student's major.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 3JM ADV; at least 10 credits of 3000/4000-level advertising courses and department permission.

COURSES.name: Advertising Undergraduate Research
COURSES.description: Mentored but self-directed work enables individuals or small groups to explore an issue of interest to them and to communicate their results to others. Depending on the topic, projects may involve inquiry, design, investigation, scholarship, discovery, or application.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3500 with a minimum grade of C.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: ACCOUNT MANAGEMENT
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: branding and social media
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Ads for Social Good
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Game Changing Ideas
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Shopper Marketing Comms
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: STEM Research
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Fashion Advertising
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: SOC Analytics& Strategy
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Agency Essentials
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Advertising Internship
COURSES.description: Complete an internship in advertising or related field with supervised on-the-job training. Requires 65 hours of work per credit, weekly progress reports, a summary report, and a supervisor's evaluation.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 and ENC 3252 and SPC 2608) or ORI 2000 with minimum grades of C and ADV major with a 2.50 minimum major GPA and department permission.

COURSES.name: Advanced Advertising Internship
COURSES.description: Structured internship program that is approved by the department as an immersion experience related to the field of advertising. Requires 65 hours of work per credit and submission of electronic portfolio, including a culminating project from the internship.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 and ENC 3252 with minimum grades of C and 4JM ADV major with a 2.50 minimum major GPA and department permission.

COURSES.name: Advertising Portfolio II: Beyond Traditional Media
COURSES.description: Portfolio II builds on Portfolio I. It is a hands-on, experiential learning course. Students create concepts and typical ad agency projects beyond traditional media and single executions. Students create integrated, experiential, digital, and shopper marketing campaigns.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: ADV 4710 with a C or better and department permission and Advertising major.
Co-req: ADV 4304.

COURSES.name: Economic Issues, Food and You
COURSES.description: The role of agriculture and economics: the how's and why's of their influence on food prices and the world food situation, the environment, natural resources and government policy; and economic issues, including inflation and money. (S)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: not for FRE majors.

COURSES.name: Economics of Resource Use
COURSES.description: Introduces how economists value the environment and regulations designed to protect our natural resources from overuse and degradation. (S)

COURSES.name: Principles of Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces the field of food and resource economics, the principles of economics as applied to agriculture, and the economic problems of the agricultural industry and the individual farmer. (S)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 2233/2311 or higher.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Agricultural Computer Applications
COURSES.description: Introduces computer application with specific emphasis on applications used in agricultural businesses. Specific applications include spreadsheets, databases, word processing and DOS.

COURSES.name: Financial Planning for Agribusiness
COURSES.description: Introduces basic financial and managerial decision-making for small agribusinesses.

COURSES.name: Principles of Agribusiness Management
COURSES.description: Introduces agribusiness management principles, application of economic principles, budgeting techniques, and principles of strategy in agribusiness from management in the United States, particularly Florida. Emphasizes the financial and tax management strategies and the requirements imposed on agribusiness management by local, state and federal government regulatory agencies.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Agricultural Finance
COURSES.description: Basic financial statements, investment frameworks and theories of financial intermediation as applied to agricultural firms, along with an overview of financial institutions that provide capital to agriculture.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3122 or ACG 2071.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Macroeconomics
COURSES.description: Introduces the world economy from a macroeconomic perspective that focuses on the links that arise from international trade and capital flows in the agricultural sector.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ECO 2013.

COURSES.name: Agricultural and Food Marketing
COURSES.description: Examines agricultural and food marketing from a system and individual firm perspective. Explores problems and issues associated with marketing functions and institutions at the industry level and with objectives and strategies of farms and agribusiness firms that market agricultural commodities and food products.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or AEB 2014 or ECO 2023 or ECO 2013.

COURSES.name: Selling Strategically
COURSES.description: Introduces professional selling techniques for all products with special emphasis given to food and agricultural products, technical systems and services.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Natural Resource and Environmental Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces natural and environmental resource economics. Emphasizes understanding economic concepts such as resource scarcity, market failure, externality, property rights and common property resources and their application to studies of forest, land, water, energy and coastal resources.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023. Credit cannot be received for both AEB 3450 and ECP 3302.

COURSES.name: Quantitative Methods in Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Develops understanding of finite mathematical tools used in economics and business decision making. Topics include linear equations, matrix algebra and calculus. Lectures and problems show how these tools are used to examine economic, financial and managerial problems.
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023, and MAC 2233 or MAC 2311.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Data Analysis in Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces analysis of agricultural data. Incorporates statistical and agricultural economic theory into the analysis of agricultural problems. Knowledge in use of spreadsheets is assumed.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 and AEB 3510 and STA 2023.

COURSES.name: Cross Media Selling
COURSES.description: Explore traditional and digital media landscapes as well as the fundamental ways to create client-centered, holistic solutions using cross media platform selling. This course will deep dive into real-life examples and scenarios as well as give students hands-on experience with this type of selling.

COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: SOC Analytics& Strategy
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Special Study in Advertising: Agency Essentials
COURSES.description: Variable advertising-related topics not covered in other advertising courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C and Advertising major of junior standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Advertising Internship
COURSES.description: Complete an internship in advertising or related field with supervised on-the-job training. Requires 65 hours of work per credit, weekly progress reports, a summary report, and a supervisor's evaluation.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 and ENC 3252 and SPC 2608) or ORI 2000 with minimum grades of C and ADV major with a 2.50 minimum major GPA and department permission.

COURSES.name: Advanced Advertising Internship
COURSES.description: Structured internship program that is approved by the department as an immersion experience related to the field of advertising. Requires 65 hours of work per credit and submission of electronic portfolio, including a culminating project from the internship.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 and ENC 3252 with minimum grades of C and 4JM ADV major with a 2.50 minimum major GPA and department permission.

COURSES.name: Advertising Portfolio II: Beyond Traditional Media
COURSES.description: Portfolio II builds on Portfolio I. It is a hands-on, experiential learning course. Students create concepts and typical ad agency projects beyond traditional media and single executions. Students create integrated, experiential, digital, and shopper marketing campaigns.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: ADV 4710 with a C or better and department permission and Advertising major.
Co-req: ADV 4304.

COURSES.name: Economic Issues, Food and You
COURSES.description: The role of agriculture and economics: the how's and why's of their influence on food prices and the world food situation, the environment, natural resources and government policy; and economic issues, including inflation and money. (S)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: not for FRE majors.

COURSES.name: Economics of Resource Use
COURSES.description: Introduces how economists value the environment and regulations designed to protect our natural resources from overuse and degradation. (S)

COURSES.name: Principles of Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces the field of food and resource economics, the principles of economics as applied to agriculture, and the economic problems of the agricultural industry and the individual farmer. (S)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 2233/2311 or higher.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Agricultural Computer Applications
COURSES.description: Introduces computer application with specific emphasis on applications used in agricultural businesses. Specific applications include spreadsheets, databases, word processing and DOS.

COURSES.name: Financial Planning for Agribusiness
COURSES.description: Introduces basic financial and managerial decision-making for small agribusinesses.

COURSES.name: Principles of Agribusiness Management
COURSES.description: Introduces agribusiness management principles, application of economic principles, budgeting techniques, and principles of strategy in agribusiness from management in the United States, particularly Florida. Emphasizes the financial and tax management strategies and the requirements imposed on agribusiness management by local, state and federal government regulatory agencies.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Agricultural Finance
COURSES.description: Basic financial statements, investment frameworks and theories of financial intermediation as applied to agricultural firms, along with an overview of financial institutions that provide capital to agriculture.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3122 or ACG 2071.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Macroeconomics
COURSES.description: Introduces the world economy from a macroeconomic perspective that focuses on the links that arise from international trade and capital flows in the agricultural sector.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ECO 2013.

COURSES.name: Agricultural and Food Marketing
COURSES.description: Examines agricultural and food marketing from a system and individual firm perspective. Explores problems and issues associated with marketing functions and institutions at the industry level and with objectives and strategies of farms and agribusiness firms that market agricultural commodities and food products.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or AEB 2014 or ECO 2023 or ECO 2013.

COURSES.name: Selling Strategically
COURSES.description: Introduces professional selling techniques for all products with special emphasis given to food and agricultural products, technical systems and services.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Natural Resource and Environmental Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces natural and environmental resource economics. Emphasizes understanding economic concepts such as resource scarcity, market failure, externality, property rights and common property resources and their application to studies of forest, land, water, energy and coastal resources.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023. Credit cannot be received for both AEB 3450 and ECP 3302.

COURSES.name: Quantitative Methods in Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Develops understanding of finite mathematical tools used in economics and business decision making. Topics include linear equations, matrix algebra and calculus. Lectures and problems show how these tools are used to examine economic, financial and managerial problems.
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023, and MAC 2233 or MAC 2311.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Data Analysis in Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Introduces analysis of agricultural data. Incorporates statistical and agricultural economic theory into the analysis of agricultural problems. Knowledge in use of spreadsheets is assumed.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 and AEB 3510 and STA 2023.

COURSES.name: Comparative World Agriculture
COURSES.description: Studies the business and economic situations of the food and agriculture sector around the world. Focuses on the historical development, the current situation and the future outlook of the food and agriculture sector. (N and S)

COURSES.name: Food and Resource Economics Seminar
COURSES.description: Introduces the Department of Food and Resource Economics and career opportunities for its graduates.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Risk Management and the Law
COURSES.description: Develops an understanding of the basic concepts of common and statutory law. Identifies and addresses current legal issues of importance at the personal and professional levels. Develops an understanding of risk and the solutions for managing risk and relates the concepts of risk management and law in limiting exposure to legal liability.

COURSES.name: Agricultural and Natural Resource Ethics
COURSES.description: Examines the political, economic, environmental and ethical value issues involved in agricultural practices and policies, including agricultural research. (H or S) (WR)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: junior or senior standing.

COURSES.name: Advanced Agribusiness Management
COURSES.description: Integration of finance and management to solve problems faced by agricultural firms and agribusinesses. In addition to lectures, students will work in small groups to identify and to analyze case studies from agricultural and rural businesses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 and AEB 3144 and agribusiness major.

COURSES.name: International Trade Policy in Agriculture
COURSES.description: Explores the role of international trade policy in agriculture and examines the effects of trade policies on domestic and international prices, consumption, production, trade and government revenues. Addresses impact of current trade issues on the agricultural sector. (S)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023.

COURSES.name: International Humanitarian Assistance
COURSES.description: Emergency assistance to developing countries to minimize losses and affect recovery. Includes legal/ethical bases; program designs promoting recovery, rather than dependence; cultural issues, including gender; and technical aspects. (N and S)

COURSES.name: International Development Policy
COURSES.description: Studies how factors such as poverty, population, technology, resources, trade, and the environment affect the human effort to develop. Discusses the roles of the public and private sectors as well as the process of policy formulation and implementation. Emphasizes the agricultural sector and its role in the process of economic development, especially in countries where problems of hunger, demographic pressure, and poverty are pervasive.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or AEB 2014 or ECO 2013 or ECO 2023.

COURSES.name: Contemporary Issues in Agribusiness Management
COURSES.description: A capstone course utilizing economic concepts to address the interaction between the political process that legislates domestic agricultural, environmental and international trade policy, micro and macro economic principles, private business decisions taken by firms in response to public policies, and ethical considerations in developing and implementing public policy.
COURSES.prerequisites: Coreq: AEB 4138 or AEB 4342.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Price Analysis and Consumer Behavior
COURSES.description: Quantitative measurement of factors affecting agricultural and resource prices; seasonal and cyclical fluctuations; index measures of price and quantity variables; theory and application of consumer behavior principles.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 and AEB 3550.

COURSES.name: Agribusiness and Food Marketing Management
COURSES.description: Application of marketing and management principles to agribusiness and food marketing problems faced by managers. Emphasis on case problems, group projects, oral presentations and written assignments.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3133 and FRE major in the agribusiness specialization.

COURSES.name: Human Resources Management in Agribusiness
COURSES.description: Issues involved in the strategic and effective management of human resources in agribusiness. Human resource management concepts and techniques designed to improve agribusiness organizational teamwork, productivity, performance and enterprise success. Course explores the unique aspects of labor management and includes application through use of case problems, triad and video techniques.

COURSES.name: International Agricultural Trade
COURSES.description: Examines the economic forces associated with trade in food and agricultural products between the US and other countries. Applies economics principles and analytical techniques to international agricultural trade and multi-national markets.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 and AEB 3510.

COURSES.name: Special Problems in Food and Resource Economics
COURSES.description: Individual study in selected problem areas of interest to the student and agreeable to the instructor.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Supervised Research in Food and Resource Economics: Supervised Research
COURSES.description: Firsthand, authentic research in food and resource economics under the supervision of a faculty member. Projects may involve inquiry, design, investigation, scholarship, discovery or application. (S-U)

COURSES.name: Honors Thesis Research in Food and Resource Economics: Honors Thesis Research
COURSES.description: Independent research in food and resource economics leading to an honors thesis. Student will be mentored by a faculty member. Projects may involve inquiry, design, investigation, scholarship, discovery or application. (S-U)
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 0 to 3; can be repeated with a change in content up to 6 credits. Prereq: junior standing, upper division GPA of 3.75 or higher and completed honors thesis proposal on file.

COURSES.name: Full-Time Practical Work Experience in Food and Resource Economics: PRACT WORK EXP IN FRE
COURSES.description: Practical work must be a new experience and related to the field of study. (S-U)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: previous arrangement with advisor and undergraduate coordinator and dean permissions.

COURSES.name: Economics of Agribusiness Decisions
COURSES.description: Comprehensive treatment of microeconomic theory and its use in managerial decision making.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: AEB 3103 or ECO 2023.
